00:04:56.161 --> 00:04:58.355
So what is blended learning?

00:04:58.355 --> 00:05:00.480
MICHAEL HORN: Let me just
give a little background.

00:05:00.480 --> 00:05:05.720
What happened around 2009, 2010
was you had a couple schools

00:05:05.720 --> 00:05:07.220
around the country
that people said,

00:05:07.220 --> 00:05:09.520
we're doing "blended
learning," and they

00:05:09.520 --> 00:05:11.110
would go to
education conferences

00:05:11.110 --> 00:05:12.760
that Jamie and I
would often be at,

00:05:12.760 --> 00:05:15.810
and they would get up on a panel
and start yelling at each other

00:05:15.810 --> 00:05:18.027
that I'm blended
learning and you're not.

00:05:18.027 --> 00:05:20.610
And it was about the stupidest
conversation you could possibly

00:05:20.610 --> 00:05:22.430
imagine happening.

00:05:22.430 --> 00:05:24.870
So what we did at
that time was we

00:05:24.870 --> 00:05:26.980
looked at about 100 schools
the people said yeah,

00:05:26.980 --> 00:05:29.200
this feels like some blended
learning is going on,

00:05:29.200 --> 00:05:32.965
talked over 100 educators and
came up with this definition.

00:05:32.965 --> 00:05:34.590
And so I'll give you
the technical one,

00:05:34.590 --> 00:05:35.930
but then I'll simplify.

00:05:35.930 --> 00:05:38.990
The technical one
has three parts.

00:05:38.990 --> 00:05:41.280
It's any time a students
in a formal education

00:05:41.280 --> 00:05:44.810
program in which they're
learning online at least

00:05:44.810 --> 00:05:48.330
part of the time where they
have some element of control

00:05:48.330 --> 00:05:51.230
over the time, the
place, the path,

00:05:51.230 --> 00:05:53.960
and/or the pace of
learning, so the student

00:05:53.960 --> 00:05:56.779
starts to be empowered
in this experience.

00:05:56.779 --> 00:05:59.320
The second part is it's got to
be at least in part in a brick

00:05:59.320 --> 00:06:03.040
and mortar location away from
home with supervision, so

00:06:03.040 --> 00:06:04.790
schools, teachers.

00:06:04.790 --> 00:06:08.340
And then the third part
is that the experiences

00:06:08.340 --> 00:06:10.920
that a student enjoys they
have to be connected somehow

00:06:10.920 --> 00:06:13.030
within a given
subject or discipline,

00:06:13.030 --> 00:06:16.270
so what you do
offline has to connect

00:06:16.270 --> 00:06:17.910
to the online experience.

00:06:17.910 --> 00:06:21.644
So in other words, when I
was in school and teachers

00:06:21.644 --> 00:06:24.060
wanted to kick me out because
I was just being distracting

00:06:24.060 --> 00:06:25.851
or I had already mastered
something in math

00:06:25.851 --> 00:06:29.030
and they'd say "go do Oregon
Trail," not blended learning.

00:06:29.030 --> 00:06:30.000
Right?

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:31.690
The deer and the
buffalo or whatever

00:06:31.690 --> 00:06:33.110
that I killed in
Oregon Trail had

00:06:33.110 --> 00:06:35.130
nothing to do with
what I was learning

00:06:35.130 --> 00:06:36.880
in the classroom
with the teacher,

00:06:36.880 --> 00:06:38.710
so those experiences
have to be connected.

00:06:38.710 --> 00:06:43.070
So the real thing is just to say
online learning blending itself

00:06:43.070 --> 00:06:45.520
into our schools with teachers.

00:06:45.520 --> 00:06:48.621
Students get some sort of
control over their learning,

00:06:48.621 --> 00:06:50.120
and those experiences
are connected.

00:06:52.920 --> 00:06:55.510
MALE SPEAKER: So where
are we on that path?

00:06:55.510 --> 00:06:58.661
Like where are things today when
it comes to blended learning?

00:06:58.661 --> 00:07:00.910
MICHAEL HORN: So blended
learning I think is exploding

00:07:00.910 --> 00:07:03.520
way more than the quote unquote,
"ed-reform conversation"

00:07:03.520 --> 00:07:06.260
actually popularly acknowledges.

00:07:06.260 --> 00:07:08.450
By some estimates, 75%
of school districts

00:07:08.450 --> 00:07:11.030
are doing some form of blended
learning across the country

00:07:11.030 --> 00:07:13.019
right now.

00:07:13.019 --> 00:07:15.310
And we're seeing really
interesting whole-school models

00:07:15.310 --> 00:07:18.490
use blended learning to
literally reinvent what they do

00:07:18.490 --> 00:07:20.770
and what the teaching and
learning experience looks

00:07:20.770 --> 00:07:24.052
like for students and teachers
in really positive ways.

00:07:24.052 --> 00:07:26.260
If we're being honest, a
lot of that blended learning

00:07:26.260 --> 00:07:28.386
is not stuff that we should
get excited about also.

00:07:28.386 --> 00:07:30.301
MALE SPEAKER: So talk a
little bit about that.

00:07:30.301 --> 00:07:31.800
What does that mean?

00:07:31.800 --> 00:07:34.260
MICHAEL HORN: I think actually
the original definition

00:07:34.260 --> 00:07:37.300
that people wanted for blended
learning was the best of online

00:07:37.300 --> 00:07:39.820
learning with the best of
brick and mortar schools,

00:07:39.820 --> 00:07:40.810
and that's great.

00:07:40.810 --> 00:07:42.500
That's what I hope
happens, but if we're

00:07:42.500 --> 00:07:44.920
being honest a lot of
things that you see out

00:07:44.920 --> 00:07:46.800
there that could
be called nothing

00:07:46.800 --> 00:07:49.630
except blended learning are not
places we would want to send

00:07:49.630 --> 00:07:51.250
our kids to necessarily.

00:07:51.250 --> 00:07:53.890
They may be just sort of Night
of The Living Dead experiences

00:07:53.890 --> 00:07:56.431
where students are clicking away
at multiple choice questions

00:07:56.431 --> 00:07:58.411
on a computer, a
teacher is there,

00:07:58.411 --> 00:08:00.410
but they're filing their
nails because they feel

00:08:00.410 --> 00:08:01.480
like they've been replaced.

00:08:01.480 --> 00:08:03.771
This isn't a good experience,
and if we're being honest

00:08:03.771 --> 00:08:05.580
there's a fair amount
of that going on.

00:08:05.580 --> 00:08:08.690
And so my sense of where
we are in this pathway

00:08:08.690 --> 00:08:11.470
is blended learning is happening
whether we like it or not.

00:08:11.470 --> 00:08:13.460
The exciting thing
about it is the ability

00:08:13.460 --> 00:08:17.330
to personalize an education for
every student's distinct needs

00:08:17.330 --> 00:08:18.940
so that they can
find their passion

00:08:18.940 --> 00:08:21.170
and realize their
potential, but we

00:08:21.170 --> 00:08:23.600
have to really be pushing
people in that quality piece

00:08:23.600 --> 00:08:27.480
now, and educating people
about the possibilities

00:08:27.480 --> 00:08:29.560
that it delivers
for the first time

00:08:29.560 --> 00:08:32.289
in human history for
every single child,

00:08:32.289 --> 00:08:34.720
but we're not there yet.

00:08:34.720 --> 00:08:37.210
MALE SPEAKER: So
talk about the role

00:08:37.210 --> 00:08:39.990
of technology in this world.

00:08:39.990 --> 00:08:42.350
Where were we, what do you
see, and what's needed?

00:08:42.350 --> 00:08:45.100
So the magic
question-- where do you

00:08:45.100 --> 00:08:49.025
see technology's role in this
blended learning environment?

00:08:49.025 --> 00:08:50.650
MICHAEL HORN: Maybe
it's useful to talk

00:08:50.650 --> 00:08:54.270
about this as a trajectory, but
where I think online learning

00:08:54.270 --> 00:08:56.440
and technology first
started in this environment

00:08:56.440 --> 00:08:59.425
was really whole
class experiences that

00:08:59.425 --> 00:09:00.800
were delivered
online where you'd

00:09:00.800 --> 00:09:04.940
write an entire curriculum
for a particular course

00:09:04.940 --> 00:09:07.330
and students would jump
on and have a teacher

00:09:07.330 --> 00:09:09.350
sort of facilitating
and tutoring

00:09:09.350 --> 00:09:12.330
alongside that experience, but
really the course curriculum

00:09:12.330 --> 00:09:15.580
was all in this package
content from one vendor.

00:09:15.580 --> 00:09:18.130
Where I think we've
started to evolve to

00:09:18.130 --> 00:09:20.650
is that teachers in
schools are actually

00:09:20.650 --> 00:09:23.230
using a variety of content
in learning experiences

00:09:23.230 --> 00:09:26.120
from online from a
variety of sources

00:09:26.120 --> 00:09:28.630
to custom configure
that learning experience

00:09:28.630 --> 00:09:29.210
for students.

00:09:29.210 --> 00:09:33.930
And so you might see a classroom
in Los Angeles, California

00:09:33.930 --> 00:09:37.666
at a school serving kindergarten
through fifth grade students

00:09:37.666 --> 00:09:39.540
where students are
rotating through a variety

00:09:39.540 --> 00:09:42.410
of experiences, one of which
is that online learning.

00:09:42.410 --> 00:09:44.060
Some kids will be
working on a program

00:09:44.060 --> 00:09:48.040
like ST Math learning math
through a visual way of playing

00:09:48.040 --> 00:09:49.020
a game.

00:09:49.020 --> 00:09:50.620
Other students will
be doing DreamBox

00:09:50.620 --> 00:09:52.020
learning-- very different way.

00:09:52.020 --> 00:09:53.436
And still, other
students might be

00:09:53.436 --> 00:09:55.680
on Khan Academy
learning math depending

00:09:55.680 --> 00:09:57.540
on their particular
point in their learning

00:09:57.540 --> 00:10:00.157
and what they're
trying to work on.

00:10:00.157 --> 00:10:01.990
And I think the big
challenge that we're now

00:10:01.990 --> 00:10:05.897
facing right now for teachers
on the ground is great,

00:10:05.897 --> 00:10:08.230
there's all these options,
there's a lot of free content

00:10:08.230 --> 00:10:11.330
out there on the web that I
can use and so forth and then

00:10:11.330 --> 00:10:14.651
connect my students with
different learning experiences,

00:10:14.651 --> 00:10:16.650
and all these things are
spitting of data for me

00:10:16.650 --> 00:10:18.441
that I can figure out
where my students are

00:10:18.441 --> 00:10:20.800
and help them navigate
different pathways.

00:10:20.800 --> 00:10:21.400
Holy cow.

00:10:21.400 --> 00:10:26.020
How do I get these software
programs to really talk

00:10:26.020 --> 00:10:27.700
to each other in a
way that's meaningful

00:10:27.700 --> 00:10:30.210
so I can do something
actionable for students.

00:10:30.210 --> 00:10:33.020
And I think that's where we are
right now where there haven't

00:10:33.020 --> 00:10:35.160
really been platforms
that have emerged yet

00:10:35.160 --> 00:10:38.660
that have helped make sense
of this very fragmented world

00:10:38.660 --> 00:10:39.560
that's emerging.

