what have you seen,

00:11:00.580 --> 00:11:03.020
how have you seen our tools
been used in education?

00:11:03.020 --> 00:11:05.311
MICHAEL HORN: I think you're
seeing Google's impact all

00:11:05.311 --> 00:11:07.900
over the place right now in
education in a couple ways.

00:11:07.900 --> 00:11:10.461
One, so in some of
the environments

00:11:10.461 --> 00:11:12.460
that are not blended
learning by our definition,

00:11:12.460 --> 00:11:16.120
but you're still starting people
experiment with technology.

00:11:16.120 --> 00:11:19.910
You're seeing Google Apps be
used sort of as that entry

00:11:19.910 --> 00:11:23.400
level what can we start to do
with technology, what can we

00:11:23.400 --> 00:11:26.460
start to pull in, what
can we start to create?

00:11:26.460 --> 00:11:30.312
And so very clearly disrupting
a lot of the software makers

00:11:30.312 --> 00:11:32.520
that were there before in
a lot of these productivity

00:11:32.520 --> 00:11:34.849
tools and Google
Apps coming in there.

00:11:34.849 --> 00:11:37.390
What I think then happens once
you move to a blended learning

00:11:37.390 --> 00:11:39.420
environment is you
start to say, how can we

00:11:39.420 --> 00:11:41.670
use time very differently?

00:11:41.670 --> 00:11:44.440
So we may want students
engaging in direct instruction

00:11:44.440 --> 00:11:46.194
in a particular
software program,

00:11:46.194 --> 00:11:47.610
but now we can
start to use Google

00:11:47.610 --> 00:11:49.640
Apps for the project
based learning,

00:11:49.640 --> 00:11:51.780
coordinate whole
aspects of learning

00:11:51.780 --> 00:11:53.420
in some pretty exciting ways.

00:11:53.420 --> 00:11:55.880
I think you're seeing
teachers use those pathways

00:11:55.880 --> 00:12:00.010
through a variety of Google
Apps in pretty neat ways,

00:12:00.010 --> 00:12:04.280
and I don't know many schools
that don't use Google Apps when

00:12:04.280 --> 00:12:06.400
they get into blended learning.

00:12:06.400 --> 00:12:09.040
The other part that I
think is really exciting

00:12:09.040 --> 00:12:13.300
that we talk about a fair amount
is the Chromebook world, which

00:12:13.300 --> 00:12:16.260
from my perspective,
Chromebooks make the most

00:12:16.260 --> 00:12:19.860
sense for the majority
of schools getting

00:12:19.860 --> 00:12:22.610
into this blended learning
game because they're not just

00:12:22.610 --> 00:12:24.897
consumption devices, they
are also creation devices,

00:12:24.897 --> 00:12:26.480
and I think that's
what separates them

00:12:26.480 --> 00:12:28.660
from a lot of the
tablets that have

00:12:28.660 --> 00:12:30.880
gotten dumped on the market.

00:12:30.880 --> 00:12:33.500
And then the price point I
think is extremely attractive,

00:12:33.500 --> 00:12:35.786
and then the way you can
manage them from the cloud

00:12:35.786 --> 00:12:37.160
is something that
I think schools

00:12:37.160 --> 00:12:40.090
have found extraordinarily
useful in terms

00:12:40.090 --> 00:12:43.260
of managing devices
that otherwise get

00:12:43.260 --> 00:12:45.990
into problems in other places.

00:12:45.990 --> 00:12:49.314
One other quick thing-- I
think your team in particular

00:12:49.314 --> 00:12:51.480
has done a good job of one
other thing, which is not

00:12:51.480 --> 00:12:53.360
to go into schools
and say, "all right,

00:12:53.360 --> 00:12:55.350
here are you Chromebooks.

00:12:55.350 --> 00:12:56.470
Go have fun."

00:12:56.470 --> 00:12:58.080
You've actually
helped people think

00:12:58.080 --> 00:13:00.780
through what's the design
process that you want

00:13:00.780 --> 00:13:03.320
to go through, what are you
actually trying to solve,

00:13:03.320 --> 00:13:07.270
and then how can our
technology-- huge range of it,

00:13:07.270 --> 00:13:11.150
right-- be marshalled to
help you solve these problems

00:13:11.150 --> 00:13:12.750
for teachers and students.

00:13:12.750 --> 00:13:16.530
And from my perspective, that's
what every school and district

00:13:16.530 --> 00:13:18.600
ought to be doing is a
much more grounds up,

00:13:18.600 --> 00:13:20.480
what are we trying
to do together,

00:13:20.480 --> 00:13:22.310
and then technology
and service of that

00:13:22.310 --> 00:13:24.950
rather than just
layer on technology.

00:13:24.950 --> 00:13:27.490
MALE SPEAKER: So by the
way, in a couple minutes

00:13:27.490 --> 00:13:29.160
I'm going to ask you
guys for question,

00:13:29.160 --> 00:13:30.380
so think of your questions.

00:13:30.380 --> 00:13:33.470
We want to make sure that we
ask Michael some questions.

00:13:33.470 --> 00:13:38.250
The one question I have for
your around blended learning

00:13:38.250 --> 00:13:40.570
is where does it usually start.

00:13:40.570 --> 00:13:42.412
Does it start in kindergarten?

00:13:42.412 --> 00:13:43.620
Does it start in third grade?

00:13:43.620 --> 00:13:46.185
Where do you see the peak of
blended learning take off?

00:13:46.185 --> 00:13:50.060
MICHAEL HORN: It's a great
question-- all over the place.

00:13:50.060 --> 00:13:54.570
And I think for a lot
of district schools

00:13:54.570 --> 00:13:57.140
it started in high
school, particularly

00:13:57.140 --> 00:13:58.600
in these areas of
non-consumption,

00:13:58.600 --> 00:14:01.510
in our language, where the
alternative is nothing at all.

00:14:01.510 --> 00:14:04.520
And I don't think people
realize this-- 50%

00:14:04.520 --> 00:14:07.830
of our high schools in this
country don't offer calculus.

00:14:07.830 --> 00:14:10.864
37% of our high schools
do not offer physics.

00:14:10.864 --> 00:14:12.280
If you're in the
state of Georgia,

00:14:12.280 --> 00:14:14.190
there's 440 high
schools roughly--

00:14:14.190 --> 00:14:17.560
there are 88 certified physics
teachers in the entire state.

00:14:17.560 --> 00:14:18.150
OK?

00:14:18.150 --> 00:14:20.230
So we can talk
about stem problems

00:14:20.230 --> 00:14:21.905
or whatever else all
we want, like we've

00:14:21.905 --> 00:14:23.030
got to get real about that.

00:14:23.030 --> 00:14:27.560
So high schools literally
need to use online learning

00:14:27.560 --> 00:14:29.560
in their schools
to connect students

00:14:29.560 --> 00:14:32.840
to highly qualified teachers and
create very different learning

00:14:32.840 --> 00:14:36.020
experiences from
that which has come

00:14:36.020 --> 00:14:38.950
before-- really important
part where a lot of this

00:14:38.950 --> 00:14:39.970
has started.

00:14:39.970 --> 00:14:42.680
I think in elementary school
you're seeing it much more

00:14:42.680 --> 00:14:44.890
in core classes--
math and reading,

00:14:44.890 --> 00:14:48.140
and in terms of what
grade level it's literally

00:14:48.140 --> 00:14:49.290
all over the map.

00:14:49.290 --> 00:14:52.030
You have great
examples all over.

00:14:52.030 --> 00:14:54.650
I think the one thing you'd say
is if you're in kindergarten

00:14:54.650 --> 00:14:58.380
I don't want my kid on the
screen for three hours a day.

00:14:58.380 --> 00:15:00.436
I'm comfortable
with 20, 30 minutes,

00:15:00.436 --> 00:15:01.810
and then if you're
in fifth grade

00:15:01.810 --> 00:15:03.518
you could do a little
bit more than that.

00:15:03.518 --> 00:15:07.330
So it's a continuum, it does not
look the same in any one place.

