00:16:18.560 --> 00:16:19.300
into a community.

00:16:19.300 --> 00:16:20.000
MALE SPEAKER: Right.

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:22.625
So a lot of what you're talking
about is here, based in the US.

00:16:22.625 --> 00:16:24.910
Do you work with school
districts across the world?

00:16:24.910 --> 00:16:29.080
And you mentioned the shortage
of classes and teachers

00:16:29.080 --> 00:16:30.760
who teach specific classes.

00:16:30.760 --> 00:16:32.640
You think about a
country like India

00:16:32.640 --> 00:16:36.130
where they are short 1.4
million teachers, right?

00:16:36.130 --> 00:16:38.590
Whatever number you want to
use, but it's more than five.

00:16:38.590 --> 00:16:41.189
So what does blended
learning look

00:16:41.189 --> 00:16:42.730
like on the
international scale, what

00:16:42.730 --> 00:16:44.080
are you seeing in that space?

00:16:44.080 --> 00:16:46.410
MICHAEL HORN: I think the
models are looking and will

00:16:46.410 --> 00:16:47.826
look very different
from what they

00:16:47.826 --> 00:16:49.990
look like in the US for
a variety of reasons.

00:16:49.990 --> 00:16:52.770
I think mobile will be a
much bigger deal as you

00:16:52.770 --> 00:16:54.240
go into emerging countries.

00:16:54.240 --> 00:16:56.100
I also think the
disruptive innovations will

00:16:56.100 --> 00:16:58.730
be much bigger that they
create, and the reason

00:16:58.730 --> 00:17:01.400
I say that is if you think
about disruptive innovation

00:17:01.400 --> 00:17:03.230
theory-- I'm making
an assumption everyone

00:17:03.230 --> 00:17:05.666
has some idea that
here-- but it starts

00:17:05.666 --> 00:17:07.040
in these areas of
non-consumption

00:17:07.040 --> 00:17:09.369
where the alternative
is truly nothing at all.

00:17:09.369 --> 00:17:13.510
In the United States we have
full consumption of schooling.

00:17:13.510 --> 00:17:15.900
Basically everyone has
a schooling option.

00:17:15.900 --> 00:17:18.839
You have non-consumption
of classes.

00:17:18.839 --> 00:17:21.950
In some of these emerging
markets in developing countries

00:17:21.950 --> 00:17:24.300
you don't have schools, or
you don't have schools that

00:17:24.300 --> 00:17:25.690
are real options in any event.

00:17:25.690 --> 00:17:27.400
Teachers don't show
up or they're too far

00:17:27.400 --> 00:17:30.600
for girls and boys to travel.

00:17:30.600 --> 00:17:33.430
So the opportunity to
bring these things and very

00:17:33.430 --> 00:17:37.410
new solutions into
communities themselves I think

00:17:37.410 --> 00:17:39.960
is an unbelievable
opportunity for innovation

00:17:39.960 --> 00:17:42.174
and it has obviously a
whole set of barriers, but--

00:17:42.174 --> 00:17:44.090
MALE SPEAKER: What are
some of those barriers?

00:17:44.090 --> 00:17:45.880
MICHAEL HORN: Well, obviously
infrastructure and access

00:17:45.880 --> 00:17:46.750
is one.

00:17:46.750 --> 00:17:49.830
I think helping the communities
know how to use it is another,

00:17:49.830 --> 00:17:53.610
and thinking about it not from
a US-centric point of view.

00:17:53.610 --> 00:17:56.660
I think we have a
certain attitude that it

00:17:56.660 --> 00:17:59.320
has to be sort of
a tablet or laptop

00:17:59.320 --> 00:18:01.290
or to be quote
unquote, "good enough."

00:18:01.290 --> 00:18:04.280
In these places
like an SMS program

00:18:04.280 --> 00:18:07.480
that helps feed the
teacher ideas for projects

00:18:07.480 --> 00:18:11.180
to do as students could be
the right learning modality

00:18:11.180 --> 00:18:11.970
in any given day.

00:18:11.970 --> 00:18:16.390
I think we have to reset
our expectations on that.

00:18:16.390 --> 00:18:19.770
I spent a fair amount of
time in Vietnam looking

00:18:19.770 --> 00:18:23.860
at this last year, and if
you look at the rural areas

00:18:23.860 --> 00:18:25.740
there's actually
lots of cellphones,

00:18:25.740 --> 00:18:28.860
but creating relevant
curriculum for those contexts

00:18:28.860 --> 00:18:30.580
you can't just
take our curriculum

00:18:30.580 --> 00:18:32.580
and like port it into a
different place and say,

00:18:32.580 --> 00:18:34.640
there we've solved it.

00:18:34.640 --> 00:18:39.220
So there's a whole bunch
of cultural, language,

00:18:39.220 --> 00:18:41.460
and circumstantial, like
actually making it relevant.

00:18:41.460 --> 00:18:43.880
I'll give a very
concrete example.

00:18:43.880 --> 00:18:47.880
In the North of Vietnam there's
a lot of tribal communities

00:18:47.880 --> 00:18:50.520
that are cut off from the rest
of the Vietnamese language

00:18:50.520 --> 00:18:52.040
and culture and so forth.

00:18:52.040 --> 00:18:54.440
Vietnam basically
makes them attend

00:18:54.440 --> 00:18:57.210
the nationalized
schools, if you will,

00:18:57.210 --> 00:18:59.050
that teach curriculum
that's totally

00:18:59.050 --> 00:19:01.880
irrelevant for their
lives and so forth.

00:19:01.880 --> 00:19:04.310
If they can learn
English though they

00:19:04.310 --> 00:19:07.700
can get ahead big time in the
tourism worlds and so forth.

00:19:07.700 --> 00:19:09.600
So basically all
these kids drop out

00:19:09.600 --> 00:19:12.910
of these government run
schools by the first grade.

00:19:12.910 --> 00:19:16.460
Don't attend, tend to
live in these very small--

00:19:16.460 --> 00:19:18.860
they laugh at us if you
and I were to walk in,

00:19:18.860 --> 00:19:24.000
because we don't
fit in their houses.

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:27.080
But super useful if they can get
access to English in a way that

00:19:27.080 --> 00:19:29.430
makes sense for their
context and teaches them

00:19:29.430 --> 00:19:32.670
things that help explain in
their environment to people

00:19:32.670 --> 00:19:35.380
like me coming through.

00:19:35.380 --> 00:19:37.340
People haven't
grappled with that.

00:19:37.340 --> 00:19:39.040
MALE SPEAKER: So I want to
turn it over to the audience,

00:19:39.040 --> 00:19:41.456
but before I do that and as
they think about the questions

00:19:41.456 --> 00:19:43.600
that they want to ask,
the question I want to ask

00:19:43.600 --> 00:19:45.500
is around professional
development.

00:19:45.500 --> 00:19:47.750
What does professional
development look

00:19:47.750 --> 00:19:49.452
like in a blended
learning environment,

00:19:49.452 --> 00:19:51.660
what are we doing right,
what are we not doing right?

00:19:51.660 --> 00:19:53.530
MICHAEL HORN: Well,
let's start with this,

00:19:53.530 --> 00:19:56.510
which is the role of
the teacher dramatically

00:19:56.510 --> 00:19:58.690
changes in these blended
learning environments.

00:19:58.690 --> 00:20:00.810
And so the first thing
to say right is teachers

00:20:00.810 --> 00:20:03.540
are absolutely critical still,
but they look different.

00:20:03.540 --> 00:20:07.380
They're not delivering a
lecture or a lesson plan

00:20:07.380 --> 00:20:10.080
to a class of 30
students who they're

00:20:10.080 --> 00:20:12.740
assuming are all on the
same place and same learning

00:20:12.740 --> 00:20:14.400
pathway.

00:20:14.400 --> 00:20:16.794
That doesn't make any
sense, because now they're

00:20:16.794 --> 00:20:18.210
all progressing
in different ways,

00:20:18.210 --> 00:20:21.340
working on different projects,
and so a teacher is serving

00:20:21.340 --> 00:20:25.196
as a tutor, a mentor,
a designer of projects,

00:20:25.196 --> 00:20:26.820
and assessors or
evaluator of learning.

00:20:26.820 --> 00:20:31.230
Very different sets of things,
maybe even a non-academic coach

00:20:31.230 --> 00:20:34.340
In many cases dealing with
all the emotional and health

00:20:34.340 --> 00:20:36.520
problems that come up in
the way and block people

00:20:36.520 --> 00:20:38.530
from learning all the
time that we don't tend

00:20:38.530 --> 00:20:41.710
to talk about in this country.

00:20:41.710 --> 00:20:43.430
It's a very different
role, and so

00:20:43.430 --> 00:20:45.250
if you talk to a
blended learning teacher

00:20:45.250 --> 00:20:47.630
you say how much of
your teacher preparation

00:20:47.630 --> 00:20:49.980
program or professional
development trained you

00:20:49.980 --> 00:20:52.740
for what you're doing now, and
they'll typically say something

00:20:52.740 --> 00:20:55.480
like I don't know, 5% of
what I learned trained me

00:20:55.480 --> 00:21:00.010
for 95% of my job, and
95% of what I learned

00:21:00.010 --> 00:21:02.840
is maybe relevant
for 5% of my job.

00:21:02.840 --> 00:21:05.280
So that's really difficult
that we're putting teachers

00:21:05.280 --> 00:21:06.750
in these circumstances.

00:21:06.750 --> 00:21:09.350
The good news, I think, is
that teachers are smart people

00:21:09.350 --> 00:21:12.530
and they over time start
to figure these things out.

00:21:12.530 --> 00:21:14.780
The bad news is like, why
do we put them through that,

00:21:14.780 --> 00:21:17.580
and can't we do a better
job supporting them?

00:21:17.580 --> 00:21:21.010
And so my sense is that,
a, the preparation programs

00:21:21.010 --> 00:21:23.250
will have to change
dramatically.

00:21:23.250 --> 00:21:26.230
Tom Arnett on our team is
doing a lot of research,

00:21:26.230 --> 00:21:28.570
he's actually speaking about
it at the EdElements Summit

00:21:28.570 --> 00:21:32.555
today on how do we moved to
new preparation programs.

00:21:32.555 --> 00:21:34.430
And then I think the
professional development

00:21:34.430 --> 00:21:37.422
should be much more personalized
for different teacher needs,

00:21:37.422 --> 00:21:39.630
just as we would personalize
professional development

00:21:39.630 --> 00:21:42.380
for students, and much
more just in time.

00:21:42.380 --> 00:21:46.130
So rather than some guy
like me writes a book,

00:21:46.130 --> 00:21:48.855
shows up at a school district
three, four times a year

00:21:48.855 --> 00:21:50.230
and does professional
development

00:21:50.230 --> 00:21:52.855
that's only tangentially related
to what the teachers are doing

00:21:52.855 --> 00:21:56.050
in the classroom that they
get access to just in time

00:21:56.050 --> 00:21:58.079
professional development
every single day

00:21:58.079 --> 00:21:59.620
with whatever
challenges that they're

00:21:59.620 --> 00:22:02.040
facing that are very tailored
to what they're doing.

00:22:02.040 --> 00:22:04.210
I think Summit Public
Schools in the Bay Area

00:22:04.210 --> 00:22:07.006
probably is the closest to
getting this right today

00:22:07.006 --> 00:22:08.380
with the professional
development

00:22:08.380 --> 00:22:10.379
that they do for teachers
in a very personalized

00:22:10.379 --> 00:22:11.900
way on their platform.

