00:24:02.362 --> 00:24:04.570
based on the number of
minutes students are in seats,

00:24:04.570 --> 00:24:06.700
so if you step back
from it for a moment

00:24:06.700 --> 00:24:08.780
you say we've been
measuring the wrong end

00:24:08.780 --> 00:24:15.460
of the student for 100
years, but we continue do so.

00:24:15.460 --> 00:24:19.120
Restrictions around
class size even,

00:24:19.120 --> 00:24:23.190
what classes look like, a lot
of the facility restrictions.

00:24:23.190 --> 00:24:26.800
We could imagine a much
different education system.

00:24:26.800 --> 00:24:29.070
A lot of the teacher-eval
policies coming on right

00:24:29.070 --> 00:24:31.760
now are counterproductive.

00:24:31.760 --> 00:24:33.320
They're very
consumed with inputs.

00:24:33.320 --> 00:24:35.650
We need to be
looking at not just

00:24:35.650 --> 00:24:38.140
student outcomes at a
point in time on a test,

00:24:38.140 --> 00:24:40.060
but actually the growth
of students over time

00:24:40.060 --> 00:24:43.830
at an individual level.

00:24:43.830 --> 00:24:47.540
I think the other thing that
we do unfairly right now is--

00:24:47.540 --> 00:24:50.832
and I'm a big believer
in the intentions

00:24:50.832 --> 00:24:52.290
behind the
accountability movement,

00:24:52.290 --> 00:24:55.860
and the power of standards
if we do it right-- but right

00:24:55.860 --> 00:24:58.790
now if students
are in fifth grade

00:24:58.790 --> 00:25:00.999
and they come in at a
second grade reading level,

00:25:00.999 --> 00:25:03.290
we test them at the end of
year with a fifth grade test

00:25:03.290 --> 00:25:05.705
and say they're now reading
at a fourth grade level.

00:25:05.705 --> 00:25:07.530
A teacher doesn't get
any credit for that.

00:25:07.530 --> 00:25:08.970
We don't get we don't see that.

00:25:08.970 --> 00:25:11.250
That's ridiculous.

00:25:11.250 --> 00:25:13.460
Like that teacher just
made two years of progress

00:25:13.460 --> 00:25:15.182
with that student,
that's amazing.

00:25:15.182 --> 00:25:16.140
We don't focus on that.

00:25:16.140 --> 00:25:18.760
We don't talk about
that, and so we

00:25:18.760 --> 00:25:21.010
need to do a much better
job of thinking about what

00:25:21.010 --> 00:25:22.190
does assessment mean.

00:25:22.190 --> 00:25:23.830
What are the rich
kinds of assessments

00:25:23.830 --> 00:25:27.590
we actually want to
see, and how do we

00:25:27.590 --> 00:25:30.034
evaluate those in a
fair and equitable way.

