right now on video.

00:27:02.120 --> 00:27:05.700
Video is useful in certain
learning circumstances,

00:27:05.700 --> 00:27:09.290
but it's actually for many
tasks a very inefficient way

00:27:09.290 --> 00:27:11.000
of learning.

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:14.746
Ironic, as I'm
being videoed, and I

00:27:14.746 --> 00:27:16.120
think we need to
think about what

00:27:16.120 --> 00:27:19.680
are short chunks of information
that cause people to interact

00:27:19.680 --> 00:27:24.349
a lot in these modalities
that actually create

00:27:24.349 --> 00:27:25.890
lots of opportunities
for interaction

00:27:25.890 --> 00:27:27.650
to build motivation,
and you actually

00:27:27.650 --> 00:27:32.080
learn through your interaction
and the explanation afterwards,

00:27:32.080 --> 00:27:35.310
not necessarily the content
that was delivered at you,

00:27:35.310 --> 00:27:38.590
because that makes you a
much more active learner.

00:27:38.590 --> 00:27:39.110
So--

00:27:39.110 --> 00:27:40.810
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:27:40.810 --> 00:27:42.980
MICHAEL HORN: Yeah, video push.

00:27:42.980 --> 00:27:44.500
Yeah, exactly,
where we think that

00:27:44.500 --> 00:27:48.630
a 10 minute video is the best
way to consume and understand

00:27:48.630 --> 00:27:49.820
content.

00:27:49.820 --> 00:27:52.520
I actually think the learning
sciences disagree strongly

00:27:52.520 --> 00:27:55.930
that, and there are certain
contexts where video

00:27:55.930 --> 00:27:58.696
is extraordinarily
useful at illuminating

00:27:58.696 --> 00:28:01.070
a certain thing that can only
be understood through video

00:28:01.070 --> 00:28:04.880
or being transported there,
but actually short tech space

00:28:04.880 --> 00:28:07.660
things that cause you to
respond and talk about things

00:28:07.660 --> 00:28:10.680
and be an active
learner, which are well

00:28:10.680 --> 00:28:13.100
suited to some of these
small devices I think

00:28:13.100 --> 00:28:17.932
can actually be a much more
powerful medium in many cases.

