00:29:59.620 --> 00:30:00.500
at this point.

00:30:00.500 --> 00:30:03.010
We've just been
talking about of course

00:30:03.010 --> 00:30:06.140
data shouldn't be used to sell
products to kids and stuff

00:30:06.140 --> 00:30:07.010
like that.

00:30:07.010 --> 00:30:10.360
Rather than making the case
for like why you as a parent

00:30:10.360 --> 00:30:13.920
you actually want your teacher
and student having access

00:30:13.920 --> 00:30:17.060
to data, and not just
like their data, right?

00:30:17.060 --> 00:30:19.570
Because it's an incredibly
empowering thing when

00:30:19.570 --> 00:30:22.800
you as a student-- let's talk
about that for a moment--

00:30:22.800 --> 00:30:24.660
can say like, I
didn't get that right,

00:30:24.660 --> 00:30:27.820
and I can do something
about it to improve myself.

00:30:27.820 --> 00:30:30.300
That's a deeply
motivating thing.

00:30:30.300 --> 00:30:32.790
We haven't done a good
job of articulating

00:30:32.790 --> 00:30:35.990
that in a way that actually is
a positive case that it make

00:30:35.990 --> 00:30:38.780
sense and people can rally
around, so I think actually

00:30:38.780 --> 00:30:41.800
the biggest thing is play
some offense on this issue

00:30:41.800 --> 00:30:47.430
and start to show
scenarios about why parents

00:30:47.430 --> 00:30:51.420
and teachers would want
this, and what it can do

00:30:51.420 --> 00:30:54.420
for learning, as opposed
to well yeah, of course

00:30:54.420 --> 00:30:57.122
we don't mean that in
sort of a defensive crouch

00:30:57.122 --> 00:30:57.830
where we've been.

