00:31:04.340 --> 00:31:07.580
or we accept the data that's
the assessment-based data that's

00:31:07.580 --> 00:31:09.827
six months old or a
year old, but we're not

00:31:09.827 --> 00:31:11.660
looking at the
performance-based data, which

00:31:11.660 --> 00:31:12.657
is the critical stuff.

00:31:12.657 --> 00:31:13.990
That's the stuff that we really.

00:31:13.990 --> 00:31:16.073
MICHAEL HORN: And I think
this whole opt-out world

00:31:16.073 --> 00:31:17.970
right now that's
happening, we need

00:31:17.970 --> 00:31:21.690
to be carving a
consensus of assessment

00:31:21.690 --> 00:31:24.100
can be a much more seamless
light touch thing that

00:31:24.100 --> 00:31:26.910
is happening constantly in
the background, and even

00:31:26.910 --> 00:31:28.157
objective ways.

00:31:28.157 --> 00:31:29.990
And yeah, it can be a
lighter footprint that

00:31:29.990 --> 00:31:33.120
is truly individually
focused and helping inform

00:31:33.120 --> 00:31:35.810
and gives us an accountability
picture, transparency,

00:31:35.810 --> 00:31:39.270
but is really about
the learning itself

00:31:39.270 --> 00:31:41.680
and people can get behind that.

00:31:41.680 --> 00:31:46.250
The assessments aren't
there today for that,

00:31:46.250 --> 00:31:49.160
but helping parents
understand we're on a road

00:31:49.160 --> 00:31:57.190
to that and not to neglect kids
in low-income circumstances

00:31:57.190 --> 00:32:00.150
who might not have the
same sort of advantages

00:32:00.150 --> 00:32:02.930
where and why
we're on a journey.

00:32:02.930 --> 00:32:05.430
But I also think it would help
to articulate it as a journey

00:32:05.430 --> 00:32:06.960
and not say that the
assessments we have

00:32:06.960 --> 00:32:08.310
today we should be happy about.

