Oh, we've got lots of questions.

00:41:23.510 --> 00:41:25.200
I want to make sure
I get them all in.

00:41:25.200 --> 00:41:25.910
AUDIENCE: Can you
talk a little bit

00:41:25.910 --> 00:41:27.840
about as we think
about the achievement

00:41:27.840 --> 00:41:31.400
gap, the role of technology
and helping to close it

00:41:31.400 --> 00:41:35.562
or potentially the risk that
it actually could worsen it,

00:41:35.562 --> 00:41:37.020
because we talked
about the ability

00:41:37.020 --> 00:41:38.770
to improve education
outcomes overall,

00:41:38.770 --> 00:41:41.061
but with the worst schools--

00:41:41.061 --> 00:41:42.810
MICHAEL HORN: Yeah,
totally good question.

00:41:42.810 --> 00:41:44.518
So I think the first
thing to acknowledge

00:41:44.518 --> 00:41:48.180
is that higher income kids are
already going to get access

00:41:48.180 --> 00:41:50.880
to these tools, and so
it's incumbent upon schools

00:41:50.880 --> 00:41:52.650
to do these things
for low income,

00:41:52.650 --> 00:41:54.900
because otherwise that
achievement gap will really

00:41:54.900 --> 00:41:56.370
widen.

00:41:56.370 --> 00:41:58.600
I think the other thing
personalized learning does

00:41:58.600 --> 00:42:01.890
is a lot of students
fall further and further

00:42:01.890 --> 00:42:05.370
behind because lessons
continue to move

00:42:05.370 --> 00:42:07.780
and you actually have a deep
fundamental misconception

00:42:07.780 --> 00:42:09.780
or misunderstanding
much earlier.

00:42:09.780 --> 00:42:13.180
And if you can actually
change that, so go back

00:42:13.180 --> 00:42:16.260
in their learning if you will,
and change that, it actually

00:42:16.260 --> 00:42:18.550
unlocks a much faster
trajectory then

00:42:18.550 --> 00:42:20.590
we give credit to
low income students

00:42:20.590 --> 00:42:24.430
typically for being able to
do, which you can give that

00:42:24.430 --> 00:42:26.930
any set of names, but I think
of it as education malpractice

00:42:26.930 --> 00:42:27.429
often.

00:42:31.160 --> 00:42:35.045
So I think the small
evidence we have actually is

00:42:35.045 --> 00:42:38.240
that unleashing this actually
causes these people we thought

00:42:38.240 --> 00:42:41.410
of as slow learners or
low on the achievement gap

00:42:41.410 --> 00:42:44.010
or whatever to actually soar
much faster than we thought

00:42:44.010 --> 00:42:45.910
was possible.

00:42:45.910 --> 00:42:49.260
I do think it will
create gaps, because it

00:42:49.260 --> 00:42:52.090
will allow the high-flyers to
go much further and faster.

00:42:52.090 --> 00:42:53.735
I think the hope is
that income is not

00:42:53.735 --> 00:42:57.590
the predictor of those
gaps, and that it's

00:42:57.590 --> 00:42:58.755
based on other factors.

00:42:58.755 --> 00:43:00.630
MALE SPEAKER: And the
number haven't changed,

00:43:00.630 --> 00:43:05.220
so if you make more
than $75,000 a year

00:43:05.220 --> 00:43:08.030
there's a 95% chance you
have internet access at home

00:43:08.030 --> 00:43:09.300
and the technology at home.

00:43:09.300 --> 00:43:11.030
If you make less
than $30,00 it's

00:43:11.030 --> 00:43:13.450
like 45% of whatever
that number is

00:43:13.450 --> 00:43:15.510
so you know that that
gap is already there,

00:43:15.510 --> 00:43:17.597
and it is possible
to make that worse.

00:43:17.597 --> 00:43:19.180
Rich school districts
have technology,

00:43:19.180 --> 00:43:20.704
poor school districts don't.

00:43:20.704 --> 00:43:21.620
That's just the facts.

00:43:21.620 --> 00:43:25.220
MICHAEL HORN: And we
also know that how

00:43:25.220 --> 00:43:28.800
students in those areas today
use this technology is not

00:43:28.800 --> 00:43:30.820
actually often positive,
because they don't have

00:43:30.820 --> 00:43:34.431
a community, teachers, parents
around them helping guide them

00:43:34.431 --> 00:43:35.930
in a productive way
on that journey,

00:43:35.930 --> 00:43:37.471
so there's plenty
of studies the just

00:43:37.471 --> 00:43:39.680
show the introduction
of technology--

00:43:39.680 --> 00:43:40.780
doesn't do anything.

00:43:40.780 --> 00:43:46.300
So we have to be very deliberate
about designing coherent models

00:43:46.300 --> 00:43:47.869
for the circumstances.

00:43:47.869 --> 00:43:48.660
MALE SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:43:48.660 --> 00:43:50.868
AUDIENCE: You talked a little
bit about over reliance

00:43:50.868 --> 00:43:52.987
on video, which kind
of made me think

00:43:52.987 --> 00:43:55.070
do you think overall in
the blended learning space

00:43:55.070 --> 00:43:56.736
that we're not
leveraging enough of what

00:43:56.736 --> 00:43:59.240
we know about behavioral
and educational psychology?

00:43:59.240 --> 00:44:01.410
Do you know, are there
any examples of programs

00:44:01.410 --> 00:44:03.410
you think are doing
that particularly well,

00:44:03.410 --> 00:44:05.530
or are there gaps
in the research

00:44:05.530 --> 00:44:07.530
that you think we're
not drawing upon enough?

00:44:07.530 --> 00:44:08.280
MICHAEL HORN: Yes.

00:44:08.280 --> 00:44:11.820
We are totally
ignoring that field.

00:44:11.820 --> 00:44:13.860
The developers,
like if you haven't

00:44:13.860 --> 00:44:15.342
heard of Richard
Mayer and his work

00:44:15.342 --> 00:44:17.050
on e-learning and the
science instruction

00:44:17.050 --> 00:44:21.010
like you are just starting
behind the eight ball.

00:44:21.010 --> 00:44:24.200
Not to say that there won't be
exceptions to that research.

00:44:24.200 --> 00:44:25.950
I think a lot of
education research

00:44:25.950 --> 00:44:28.470
is pretty deeply flawed
because it looks at the average

00:44:28.470 --> 00:44:32.360
as opposed to be
anomalies and comes up

00:44:32.360 --> 00:44:33.930
with a circumstance-based
theory,

00:44:33.930 --> 00:44:36.530
but there's a lot
of good research

00:44:36.530 --> 00:44:38.530
that can boost you
up dramatically

00:44:38.530 --> 00:44:41.490
to start with, and then
explore anomalies from there.

00:44:41.490 --> 00:44:45.390
And I think most people are
totally ignoring what we know.

00:44:45.390 --> 00:44:49.800
There are a few good
providers out there based

00:44:49.800 --> 00:44:51.010
on different facets of it.

00:44:51.010 --> 00:44:53.650
I think ST Math
does it pretty well.

00:44:53.650 --> 00:44:56.762
But there's a huge
gap in that right now.

00:44:56.762 --> 00:44:58.220
MALE SPEAKER: And
not just that, we

00:44:58.220 --> 00:45:00.910
have 40 years of
research and evidence

00:45:00.910 --> 00:45:03.300
about like what really good
learning can look like,

00:45:03.300 --> 00:45:06.177
and I think technology can
help us actually implement

00:45:06.177 --> 00:45:06.760
a lot of that.

00:45:06.760 --> 00:45:09.527
We have just been ignoring
it, or the positive way

00:45:09.527 --> 00:45:11.110
of saying it is that
technology hasn't

00:45:11.110 --> 00:45:13.240
been ready to use to implement.

00:45:13.240 --> 00:45:15.799
I'm the glass half-full
guy, he's the empty glass.

00:45:15.799 --> 00:45:16.840
MICHAEL HORN: Just there.

