coming down on the students
for that, and in some ways

00:45:37.660 --> 00:45:41.110
it seems like there's too
much information that is not

00:45:41.110 --> 00:45:43.380
being dealt with between
student and teacher

00:45:43.380 --> 00:45:45.700
before it's dealt with
between student and family.

00:45:45.700 --> 00:45:48.610
MICHAEL HORN: Yeah,
so I'm not sure

00:45:48.610 --> 00:45:50.800
the connection to parents
that should be made there.

00:45:50.800 --> 00:45:54.430
I think that's probably another
design choice that should

00:45:54.430 --> 00:45:55.950
be made within the schools.

00:45:55.950 --> 00:45:57.820
I more meant with
in terms of what

00:45:57.820 --> 00:45:59.930
it can do for teachers
to more effectively work

00:45:59.930 --> 00:46:02.760
with students and students to
be more effectively motivated.

00:46:02.760 --> 00:46:06.340
One thing we also know from
the research that people ignore

00:46:06.340 --> 00:46:10.010
is that data is not necessarily
a motivating force in learning,

00:46:10.010 --> 00:46:11.300
so let me explain.

00:46:11.300 --> 00:46:16.010
If you give a student data
and they have no ability

00:46:16.010 --> 00:46:17.990
to do anything with
that data, it just

00:46:17.990 --> 00:46:21.970
says you got a
70%, that is deeply

00:46:21.970 --> 00:46:24.280
demotivating to learning.

00:46:24.280 --> 00:46:26.410
If it says, you
haven't mastered this,

00:46:26.410 --> 00:46:29.110
and this is the particular area,
now go back and work again,

00:46:29.110 --> 00:46:31.200
so what we call a
competency-based or

00:46:31.200 --> 00:46:34.010
mastery-based learning
system then data

00:46:34.010 --> 00:46:38.280
is deeply motivating as you
can do something with it.

00:46:38.280 --> 00:46:41.450
And so that's the type of
data and the type of system

00:46:41.450 --> 00:46:44.450
that we actually need to use
it in to empower learners

00:46:44.450 --> 00:46:48.990
to understand where they
are going in their learning,

00:46:48.990 --> 00:46:51.010
and so that they can
constantly be using it

00:46:51.010 --> 00:46:52.700
to improve with their teachers.

00:46:52.700 --> 00:46:54.680
How that works with
parents, I think

00:46:54.680 --> 00:46:59.700
that's a community by community
decision that make sense,

00:46:59.700 --> 00:47:02.660
but it also changes.

00:47:02.660 --> 00:47:05.400
It's sort of like think of
it as a, b, or try again.

00:47:07.057 --> 00:47:09.640
We're going to eliminate letter
grades as we know if we really

00:47:09.640 --> 00:47:11.906
get this right,
because we really

00:47:11.906 --> 00:47:14.030
ought to be mastering
something before you move on.

00:47:14.030 --> 00:47:17.390
Sal Khan gives the great analogy
like you wouldn't be like,

00:47:17.390 --> 00:47:20.155
we're building a house,
well, I got 80% of it right,

00:47:20.155 --> 00:47:23.882
so let's move on to
the second floor now.

00:47:23.882 --> 00:47:25.340
But that's how we
do it in schools,

00:47:25.340 --> 00:47:30.511
and those gaps create huge
problems later in learning.

00:47:30.511 --> 00:47:32.260
MALE SPEAKER: You don't
even need a house.

00:47:32.260 --> 00:47:36.050
In our own work world,
if some one on a team

00:47:36.050 --> 00:47:38.480
hands one of us the
strategy and we're like,

00:47:38.480 --> 00:47:41.840
oh, this is about a C
plus, next assignment.

00:47:41.840 --> 00:47:43.260
No, you iterate.

00:47:43.260 --> 00:47:46.280
You change it.

00:47:46.280 --> 00:47:49.490
AUDIENCE: So I think in
education over the last 50,

00:47:49.490 --> 00:47:53.140
60 years the publishers have
really been the big players,

00:47:53.140 --> 00:47:56.070
and as they're
grappling with this move

00:47:56.070 --> 00:47:59.970
I think you see the pitfall
oftentimes of a textbook just

00:47:59.970 --> 00:48:00.930
being digitized.

00:48:00.930 --> 00:48:01.930
MICHAEL HORN: Yes.

00:48:01.930 --> 00:48:03.570
AUDIENCE: So I'm
curious if you were

00:48:03.570 --> 00:48:05.700
to jump in as the
CEO of a Pearson

00:48:05.700 --> 00:48:08.340
or an H&amp;H or McGraw
Hill, where would you

00:48:08.340 --> 00:48:11.180
take that digital content
strategy as a whole?

00:48:11.180 --> 00:48:12.425
MICHAEL HORN: Oh, God.

00:48:12.425 --> 00:48:14.800
MALE SPEAKER: Why couldn't
you ask that like an hour ago?

00:48:14.800 --> 00:48:16.716
MICHAEL HORN: Talk about
jobs I wouldn't want.

00:48:16.716 --> 00:48:17.260
OK.

00:48:17.260 --> 00:48:19.260
So I think the lessons
of destruction are clear.

00:48:19.260 --> 00:48:24.259
When you want to be the
one to disrupt yourself,

00:48:24.259 --> 00:48:26.300
you can't do it within
your current organization.

00:48:26.300 --> 00:48:29.320
You have to set up an
autonomous organization that has

00:48:29.320 --> 00:48:32.470
the freedom to rethink
everything and can ask

00:48:32.470 --> 00:48:35.640
the parent for things, but
cannot be commanded to do

00:48:35.640 --> 00:48:38.430
things by the parent,
and so if I were them,

00:48:38.430 --> 00:48:41.530
I would set up truly autonomous
business models that could say

00:48:41.530 --> 00:48:43.724
yes, we want to draw
upon your rich resources,

00:48:43.724 --> 00:48:46.140
but we're not going to be told
how we're going to use them

00:48:46.140 --> 00:48:48.780
or deploy them and we are
going to have very different

00:48:48.780 --> 00:48:54.050
processes and priorities
inside to do this.

00:48:54.050 --> 00:48:56.430
And that's how I
would approach it.

00:48:56.430 --> 00:48:59.970
I also think our policymakers
would do us a great service

00:48:59.970 --> 00:49:03.320
if they stopped talking
about digital textbooks,

00:49:03.320 --> 00:49:06.740
because that's not what
we're trying to do here.

00:49:06.740 --> 00:49:09.155
MALE SPEAKER: So speaking
of digital textbooks

00:49:09.155 --> 00:49:10.780
I want you to think
about that question

00:49:10.780 --> 00:49:13.510
I was going to ask you, I
also want to plug your book.

00:49:13.510 --> 00:49:16.510
If you are like my kid who
